<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4" style="color: #7B2D8E;">What To Expect</h2>

<p class="mb-6">
  There are a few things to be aware of when you go into your full face wax appointment. If you have never received a facial wax before, call the studio for their specific tips and recommendations on jumping into full facial waxing.
</p>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4" style="color: #7B2D8E;">Before Your Appointment</h3>

<div class="bg-gray-50 p-6 rounded-lg mb-8">
  <p class="mb-4">
    If you are on medications containing high-strength topical Vitamin A or high-strength acne medications, like Accutane, avoid getting a facial wax. Wait until you are off these medications for at least six months before scheduling a waxing appointment.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Avoid chemical peels, microdermabrasion treatments, laser treatments, fillers, anti-wrinkle injectables, or topical skin care products containing Retinol, Retin-A, Steroids, or Hydroquinone for at least two weeks before your wax. Avoiding these products sets your skin up to handle the waxing session perfectly.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Do not use skin products containing AHA or BHA for at least one week before the full face wax. Avoid granular scrubs and harsh facial scrubbing as well.
  </p>
  <p>
    When you arrive at the studio on the day of your wax appointment, arrive barefaced without any makeup on. The studio will likely cleanse the face of any unwanted oils, sunscreens, or moisturizers before the wax, but arriving barefaced helps speed up the process.
  </p>
</div>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4" style="color: #7B2D8E;">During Your Appointment</h3>

<div class="bg-purple-50 p-6 rounded-lg mb-8">
  <p class="mb-4">
    Once you are cleansed and prepped, the waxing specialist will ask you to lie down, so they can look at your face and properly assess what areas should be waxed. This step is most crucial for the eyebrows! They will ask a few questions about your preferences, skin concerns, and waxing experience to be sure you are on the same page about your treatment plan and what to expect.
  </p>
  <p>
    You can expect certain areas, like the lip and the eyebrow, to be more painful than areas with thicker skin, like the forehead or chin. The skin is more delicate, and the hair is usually more coarse in those spots, causing more discomfort.
  </p>
</div>

<h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4" style="color: #7B2D8E;">After Your Appointment</h3>

<div class="bg-gray-50 p-6 rounded-lg mb-8">
  <p class="mb-4">
    After waxing, follow any instructions your specialist gives you. It is a good idea to avoid wearing makeup, touching your face, or putting other products on for the first 12-24 hours after a facial. Waxing opens your pores. Dirt, debris, and bacteria are more likely to invade your pores in this first-day window.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Your skin will likely be a little pink immediately following the session, but this is normal and is likely due to hair removal. Contact the studio or your dermatologist if you experience irritation or abnormal redness after your wax.
  </p>
  <p>
    Your wax should last anywhere from 2-4 weeks.
  </p>
</div>

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4" style="color: #7B2D8E;">Aftercare Instructions</h2>

<div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
